  <h3>LL-37 (Human Cathelicidin)</h3>
  <p style="font-size:14px;margin-bottom:0;"><strong>Type:</strong> Cationic antimicrobial peptide &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Length:</strong> 37 amino acids &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Weight:</strong> ~4.5 kDa &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Gene Source:</strong> CAMP gene &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Parent Protein:</strong> hCAP18 &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Production Sites:</strong> Neutrophils, epithelial cells, macrophages, keratinocytes &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>Half-life:</strong> 2&ndash;4 hours in tissues &nbsp;|&nbsp; <strong>FDA Status:</strong> Not approved for therapeutic use</p>
</div>

<p>LL-37 is the only cathelicidin antimicrobial peptide found in humans. It's cut from a larger precursor protein called hCAP18 by proteinase 3, and the cleavage happens when your body senses a threat (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/14656978/">Zanetti, 2004</a>).</p>

<p>The name comes from its structure. "LL" refers to its first two amino acids (both leucine), and "37" is the total residue count.</p>

<p>Scientists first isolated it from white blood cells. Now we know it's produced across many tissues: your skin, lungs, <a href="/articles/best-peptides-for-gut-health">gut lining</a>, and urinary tract all make it.</p>

<p>For a deeper compound profile, visit <a href="https://peptidearc.com">PeptideArc</a>.</p>

