<h3>Direct Antimicrobial Action</h3>

<p>LL-37 carries a net positive charge of +6. This is critical because bacterial membranes carry a net negative charge, while human cell membranes are mostly neutral (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/16355490/">Durr et al., 2006</a>).</p>

<p>The killing process follows a clear sequence. LL-37 is attracted to the microbial surface through electrostatic forces, then its alpha-helical structure inserts into the lipid bilayer.</p>

<p>Once embedded, it forms pores that rupture the membrane. Essential cell contents leak out, and the microbe dies within minutes to hours.</p>

<div class="d-t">
  <div class="s">Research Finding</div>
  <p>LL-37 kills over 90% of common skin bacteria (including <em>S. aureus</em> and <em>E. coli</em>) within 2 hours of contact, faster than many conventional antibiotics (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/11500487/">Turner et al., 1998</a>).</p>
</div>

<p>Human cells are largely spared from this attack. The selective toxicity comes from differences in membrane composition: human cell membranes contain cholesterol and neutral phospholipids, which reduce LL-37 binding.</p>

<h3>Immune System Coordination</h3>

<p>Beyond direct killing, LL-37 acts as a signaling molecule for your broader immune response. It recruits neutrophils, monocytes, and T-cells to infection sites through chemotaxis (<a href="https://pubmed.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/17336380/">Vandamme et al., 2012</a>).</p>

<p>It also neutralizes lipopolysaccharide (LPS), a dangerous bacterial toxin that can trigger septic shock. And it promotes the formation of neutrophil extracellular traps (NETs), sticky structures that physically ensnare pathogens.</p>

<p>At low concentrations, LL-37 modulates immunity without killing anything. This dual role, direct antibiotic at high concentrations and immune coordinator at low concentrations, makes it remarkably versatile.</p>

